Variables:
•	The variables are nothing but containers / memory blocks to stores the data
•	Variable are used to store data(any kind of data)

•	Case-sensitive
•	Start With letters, (under_score), $(dollarsign)
•	Constant start with numbers
•	Reserved words (keywords) not allowed
•	Allow letters, _(under_score) , $(dollarsign) , numbers

Types of variables
•	Var() (1995) – used only old browsers
•	// var name= "ramu"
•	
•	        // name="sam"
•	
•	        // console.log(name)
•	        // console.log(name)
•	        // document.write(name)

Example2:
 var a=1
        a=5
        console.log(a+a)

Note:
•	Reassigning with var and let is also possible
let a=1
              a=5
                console.log(a+a)

•	Reassigning with const is not possible
•	const a=1
•	        a=5
•	        console.log(a+a)
Error:

basic.html:19 Uncaught TypeError: Assignment to constant variable. at basic.html:19:10

	

•	Redeclaring possible with var 
Example:
 var a=1
  var a=5
  console.log(a+a)

•	Redeclaring with let is not accepted
•	let a=1
•	        let a=5
•	        console.log(a+a)
output : Error 

•	Redeclaring with const is not accepted
•	 const a=1
•	        const  a=5
•	        console.log(a+a)
•	Output:error


	
		


•	Let (es6)-(2015)
•	Const (es6)
Intentifiers:
Intentifiers name given to variables.

Block Scope:

Var don’t have block scope:
var a="john"
        {
            var a="ramu"
            console.log(a)
            console.log(a)
            
        }
        console.log(a)
        console.log(a)

 var a=11
        var a=3 
        {
            var a=5
            console.log(a+a)
            console.log(a+a)
            
            
        }
        console.log(a+a)//10 dont have block scope

        
ex3:
var a=11
        var a=3
        {
            var a=5
            a=a+5//10  
            console.log(a+a)//20
            
            
            
        }
        console.log(a+a)//20


let have block scope:
 let a="john"
        {
            let a="ramu"
            console.log(a)
            console.log(a)
            
        }
        console.log(a)
example2:


        let a=11
        {
            let a=5
            console.log(a+a)
            console.log(a+a)
            
            
        }
        console.log(a+a)
        console.log(a+a)




